  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">The physical origin of this self-interaction <math altimg="si93.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi>O</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> term is attributed to the distortion of the body's long-range Coulomb field by the curved black-hole spacetime [11,13,15]</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">16</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">We recall that the parameters <math altimg="si94.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>a</mi><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></math> are the mass and angular momentum per unit mass of the original Kerr black hole</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">17</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">That is, Kerr black holes in the regime (14) are characterized by the relation <math altimg="si95.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo>∂</mo><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>BH</mtext></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mo>∂</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>J</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Q</mi></mrow></msub><mo></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">18</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">It is important to emphasize that our assumption <math altimg="si96.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msubsup><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow><mrow><mtext>min</mtext></mrow></msubsup><mo>≪</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msub></math>, [see Eq. (10)] corresponds to charged particles in the regime <math altimg="si97.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>≪</mo><mi>μ</mi><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msub></math></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">19</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">The expression (16) for the minimal energy delivered to the black hole by the charged body is universal in the sense that it is independent of the black-hole rotation parameter <math altimg="si98.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover></math></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">20</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">The expression (17) for the dimensionless physical quantity <math altimg="si99.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="normal">Θ</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>min</mtext></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> is universal in the sense that it is independent of the black-hole rotation parameter <math altimg="si98.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">¯</mo></mrow></mover></math></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">21</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">It is worth noting that, for generic values of the dropping height <math altimg="si32.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></math> and in the regime <math altimg="si100.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>≪</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math>, one finds from Eqs. (2), (11), (12), and (13), the relation <math altimg="si101.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mi mathvariant="normal">Θ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo></subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">22</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="m">That is, the simple inequality (18) is based on the assumption [3] that the proper distance of the body's center of mass from the black-hole horizon at the dropping point can approach arbitrarily close to the limiting value <math altimg="si103.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">→</mo><msup><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>min</mtext></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mi>q</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>μ</mi></math> [see Eq. (15)]</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
    <subfield code="o">23</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
